    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA256-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu poruḷvayiṉ pirintāṉ eṉṟu āṟṟāḷākiya takamakaḷait talaimakaṉ āṟṟiyatu (ET: āṟṟuvittatu).</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how HE calmed down HER who was unable to bear that he would separate for the sake of wealth.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA256">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            nīyē, pāṭal cāṉṟa paḻitapu cīṟaṭip</l>
<l>            palkuṟap perunalat tamartta kaṇṇai</l>
<l>            kāṭē, niḻalkavi ṉaḻinta vaḻalkavar maratta</l>
<l>            pulampuvīṟ ṟiruntu nalañcitain taṉavē</l>
<l>            yinnilai tavirntaṉañ celavē vainnutik </l>
<l>            kaḷavuṭaṉ kamaḻap piṭavuttaḷai yaviḻak</l>
<l>            kārceyal ceyta kāmar kālai</l>
<l>            maṭappiṇai taḻīiya māverut tiralai</l>
<l>            kāḻkoḷ vēlat tāḻciṉai payanta</l>
<l>            kaṇkavar variniḻal vatiyun </l>
<l>            taṇpaṭu kāṉamun tavirntaṉañ celavē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>You,</l>
<l>you have eyes at strife [with your ears]<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">amartta kaṇṇai</term>: this probably is an elliptical simile that can be understood in two ways. Either it is an allusion to the established description of HER eyes being like two carps standing opposite to each other (cf. KT 250.5: <term xml:lang="ta">poru kayal muraṇiya uṇ kaṇ</term>), or it could be a reference to the Sanskrit topos of eyes being so wide as to go right upt to the ears.</note>, increasingly<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">palkuṟa</term>: actually this form is awkward. It has to be analysed as <term xml:lang="ta">palku</term> (v.r. "to increase") plus the inf. of <term xml:lang="ta">uṟa</term>, which can be interpreted as an adverb to <term xml:lang="ta">peru</term>, but then what is the function of <term xml:lang="ta">uṟu</term> here? (The <term xml:lang="ta">alku</term> "abiding" of ER definitely looks like a simplification.)</note> great beauty,</l>
<l>faultless small feet worthy of song.</l>
<l>The wilderness,</l>
<l>[its] excellences have come to naught, distinguished by loneliness,</l>
<l>with [its] fire-seized trees, the beauty of shade perished.</l>
<l>In this state we refrained from going.</l>
<l>And we have refrained from going to the forest with cool wells,</l>
<l rend="indent3">where the big-necked Iralai, embraced by [its] youthful doe,</l>
<l rend="indent3">abides in the eye-seizing dappled shade</l>
<l rend="indent4">yielded by the sinking branches of the hard-cored Vēlam tree,</l>
<l rend="indent4">at the desirable time when the rainy season has done [its] work,</l>
<l rend="indent4">for the Piṭavu to open [its] bonds,</l>
<l rend="indent4">for the sharp-tipped Kaḷavu to be fragrant.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
